&lt;p/&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In that situation, everything is perfect.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So here is my question: don&apos;t you think we should consider making spring-jdbc and spring-aop optional?&lt;br/&gt;
People would just declare spring-aop and spring-jdbc when they need those dependencies (many people don&apos;t need them anyway).&lt;/p&gt;

</comment>
                            <comment id="93057" author="rwinch" created="Sun, 25 Aug 2013 13:25:54 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=michael.isvy&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;michael.isvy&quot;&gt;Michael Isvy&lt;/a&gt; I am proposing making spring-jdbc and spring-tx optional on the spring-security-web module and removing spring-aop as a direct dependency of spring-security-web.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Note that spring-aop still exists as a transitive dependency from spring-security-core which I think makes sense. Many of the spring-security-core components (i.e. SecurityMetadataSource) rely on spring-aop&apos;s AopInfrastructureBean. This means that spring-aop is not optional for the spring-security-core module.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Please let me know if these changes seem fitting and what you had in mind or if you have additional feedback.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="93060" author="michael.isvy" created="Sun, 25 Aug 2013 15:47:33 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hi Rob,&lt;br/&gt;
it is better like this, but I still need to explicitly declare the spring-aop dependency nearly all the time (so I expect many people will still make a mistake there). &lt;br/&gt;
I know that&apos;s probably as far as we can go with Maven, but I would still suggest a couple of more things:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;1) make the documentation as clear as possible so people can google that issue easily (I&apos;d be glad to help if you&apos;d like)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;2) IMO, we should still consider relying on the latest version of Spring by default. Reason is: if I&apos;m using Spring 3.2.3 internally and did not declare spring-aop explicitly, I still prefer to have spring-aop-3.2.2 or spring-aop 3.2.4 that comes with Spring Security by default, rather than having spring-aop-3.0.7 as it is the case now (because 3.0.7 is old and there is bigger risk that it is incompatible with a recent version of spring-core or spring-beans). &lt;br/&gt;
I see that it is also the way Spring Batch is working: it has a default dependency to Spring 3.2.0.RELEASE.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;http://search.maven.org/#artifactdetails&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;http://search.maven.org/#artifactdetails&lt;/a&gt;|org.springframework.batch|spring-batch-parent|2.2.1.RELEASE|pom&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Cheers,&lt;br/&gt;
Michael.&lt;/p&gt;

</comment>
                            <comment id="93061" author="rwinch" created="Sun, 25 Aug 2013 15:52:22 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=michael.isvy&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;michael.isvy&quot;&gt;Michael Isvy&lt;/a&gt; The current plan is that Spring Security 3.2 will depend on the latest Spring 3.2.x as a minimum version. It will support Spring 4.x, but will not update the pom&apos;s to specify Spring 4 as the dependency. Does this fit what you had in mind?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="93062" author="michael.isvy" created="Sun, 25 Aug 2013 16:12:56 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Yes, that sounds good!&lt;br/&gt;
So I guess Spring Security 4.x (on the day it&apos;ll be out) will rely on the latest Spring 4.x, right?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="93063" author="rwinch" created="Sun, 25 Aug 2013 16:15:51 +0000"  >&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;So I guess Spring Security 4.x (on the day it&apos;ll be out) will rely on the latest Spring 4.x, right?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Yes..that is the current plan&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="93066" author="rwinch" created="Sun, 25 Aug 2013 22:42:03 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Tracking will be based on &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/browse/SEC-2229&quot; title=&quot;Cleanup Optional Dependencies&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;SEC-2229&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;SEC-2229&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=michael.isvy&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;michael.isvy&quot;&gt;Michael Isvy&lt;/a&gt; Can you please verify that the updates are what you were expecting. You should be able to see the updates in the snapshot repo &lt;a href=&quot;https://repo.springsource.org/libs-snapshot/org/springframework/security/spring-security-web/3.2.0.CI-SNAPSHOT/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;https://repo.springsource.org/libs-snapshot/org/springframework/security/spring-security-web/3.2.0.CI-SNAPSHOT/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
